        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The triangles <m>OPA,\,OQB,\,\text{and }\, ORC</m> are similar.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This means that the ratios of their corresponding sides are equal: <me>\frac{PA}{OA}=\frac{QB}{OB}=\frac{RC}{OC}=\frac{15}{10}=1.5</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For any line parallel to <m>BQ</m>, rthe ratio of vertical distance to horizontal distance remains the same in each triangle. 
                        In this case, the ratio is<m>1.5</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This constant ratio, <m>\frac{\text{Vertical distance}}{\text{Horizontal distance}}</m> is called the <m>\textbf{tangent of angle} \, VOT</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Therefore, the tangent of <m>x^\circ</m> is <m>1.5</m> which can be written as: <me>\text{tan}\,x^\circ=1.5</me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The tangent of an angle depends only on the size of the angle, not on the triangle's size.
                    </p>
                </li>
                
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            The diagram below shows a right-angled triangle <m>ABC</m>, where: <me>\angle ABC = \theta</me>. 
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="figure3">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="=50%">
            <latex-image label="Triangle4">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Points
                    \coordinate (A) at (5,0);
                    \coordinate (B) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (C) at (5,3);

                    % Triangle
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

                    % Right angle box at A
                    \draw (A) -- ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);

                    % Angle theta at B
                    \draw [blue,very thick](1,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=30,radius=1cm];
                    \node [right]at (0.9,0.3) {\(\theta\)};

                    % Angle alpha at C
                    \draw [blue,very thick](4.3,2.6) arc[start angle=225,end angle=270,radius=1cm];
                    \node at (4.6,2.2) {\(\alpha\)};

                    % Labels
                    \node[ left] at (B) {B};
                    \node[right] at (A) {A};
                    \node[ right] at (C) {C};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The side <m>AC</m> is the vertical side, 
                        which is <m>\textbf{opposite}</m> to angle <m>\theta</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The side <m>AB</m> is the horizontal side, 
                        which is <m>\textbf{adjacent}</m> to angle <m>\theta</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The side <m>BC</m> is the <m>\textbf{hypotenuse}</m>, which is the longest side 
                        of the right-angled triangle.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>

        </p>
        <p>
            In this case, the tangent of angle <m>\theta</m> is defined as the ratio 
            of the opposite side to the adjacent side: 
            <me>\text{tan}\,\theta = \frac{\textbf{Opposite side}}{\textbf{Adjacent side}}= \frac{AC}{AB}</me>.
        </p>
        
        
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the tangent of the indicated
                    angles using the given
                    measurements below.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="Triangle7">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
                       % Draw the triangle
                        \draw[very thick,fill=white] (0,0) -- (4.1,0) -- (0,3.1) -- cycle;

                        % Labels for points
                        \node[above] at (0,3) {\textbf{P}};
                        \node[left] at (0,0) {\textbf{Q}};
                        \node[right] at (4,0) {\textbf{R}};

                        % Side labels
                        \node[left] at (0,1.5) {3 cm};
                        \node[below] at (2,0) {4 cm};

                        % Right angle marker
                        \draw (0,0) -- (0.3,0) -- (0.3,0.3) -- (0,0.3) -- cycle;

                        % Angle theta arc
                        \draw[thick] (4,0) arc[start angle=10, end angle=180, radius=0.2cm]; 
                        \node[right] at (3.,0.2) {\(\theta\)};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The above diagram the sides given are,
                </p>
                <p>
                    Opposite side <m>=3\,cm</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Adjacent side <m>= 4\,cm</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore,
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{tan} \, \theta = \amp  \frac{\text{Opposite }}{\text{Adjacent }} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3\,cm}{4\,cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp \frac{3}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp  0.75 </mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <m>\text{tan} \,\theta=0.75</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the tangent in the indicated angle below.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="Triangle8">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2,black]
                         % Define points
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (6,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (3,5);
                        \coordinate (D) at (3,0); % Foot of the perpendicular

                        % Draw triangle
                        \draw [very thick,fill=white] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Draw height
                        \draw [very thick,dashed] (C) -- (D);
                        
                        % Right angle symbol at D
                        \draw [very thick](D) ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);

                        % Draw angle arcs
                        \draw [very thick,blue](A) ++(0.8,0) arc (0:60:0.8); % Alpha (angle CAD)
                        \draw [very thick,blue](C) ++(-0.3,-0.5) arc (200:300:0.2); % Theta (angle ACD)

                        % Labels
                        \node[left] at (A) {\huge{$A$}};
                        \node[above] at (C) {\huge{$C$}};
                        \node[below] at (B) {\huge{$B$}};
                        \node[below] at (D) {\huge{$D$}};
                        
                        % Side lengths
                        \node[above left] at (1.5,2.5) {\huge{$5$ cm}};
                        \node[above right] at (4.5,2.5) {\huge{$5$ cm}};
                        \node[below] at (1.5,0) {\huge{$3$ cm}};
                        \node[below] at (4.5,0) {\huge{$3$ cm}};
                        
                        % Angle labels
                        \node at (0.9,0.4) {\huge{$\alpha$}};  % Alpha near A
                        \node [right]at (2.5,4) {\huge{$\theta$}}; % Theta near C
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The first thing you should do is to calculate the perpendicular height of the Triangle then identify the opposite and the adjacent sides of angle 
                    <m> \theta</m> and angle <m>\alpha</m>. Finaly find there tangents.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Finding the perpendicular height.

                </p>
                <p>
                    We use pythagorean relationship that is <me>H^2=b^2+h^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> h^2=\amp H^2-b^2 </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 5^2=3^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 25-9 </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 16 </mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{h^2}= \amp \sqrt{16} </mrow>
                        <mrow>h= \amp 4\,cm </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    Finding <m>\text{tan} \theta</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\text{tan} \, \theta =  \frac{\text{Opposite }}{\text{Adjacent }}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The opposite side <m>=3\,cm</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The adjacent side <m>=4\,cm</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{tan} \, \theta= \amp \frac{3\,cm}{4\,cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp  \frac{3}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 0.75</mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Finding <m>\text{tan} \alpha</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\text{tan} \, \alpha =  \frac{\text{Opposite }}{\text{Adjacent }}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The opposite side <m>=4\,cm</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The adjacent side <m>=3\,cm</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{tan} \, \theta= \amp \frac{4\,cm}{3\,cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp  \frac{4}{3}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp  1.3333333333</mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp  1\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore,
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{tan} \, \theta= \amp 0.75</mrow>
                        <mrow> \text{tan} \, \alpha=\amp 1.333</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                    
                
            </solution>
            
        </example>


