        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            When you look at the tables of Cosine and sine, you will notice that,
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="i)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The values of their sines increase from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The values of their cosines decrease from <m>1</m> to <m>0</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, the values in the difference
            column of <term>cosine </term> tables have to be
            subtracted and those in the difference
            columns of the <term>sine </term> tables have to be
            added.
        </p>
        <p>
            Generally, 
        </p>
        <p>
            The values of sine and cosine ranges from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>(<m>0\leq \theta \leq 1</m>).
        </p>
        <p>
            As the angles increase
            from <m>0^\circ</m> to <m>90^\circ</m>:
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Read the sine and cosine values of the
                    following angles from the tables.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>46^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>45.5^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>75.67^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>sin\,46^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Locate <m>46^\circ</m>in the sine and cosine table.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Read the corresponding sine value. That is <me>sin\,46^\circ= 0.7193</me>,
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>cos\,46^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                             <p>
                                Read the corresponding cosine value. That is <me>cos\,46^\circ= 0.6947</me>,
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>sin\,45.5^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Locate <m>45.5^\circ</m>in the sine and cosine table.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Read the corresponding sine value. That is <me>sin\,45.5^\circ= 0.7133</me>,
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>cos\,45.5^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Read the corresponding cosine value. That is <me>cos\,45.5^\circ= 0.7009</me>,
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                
                                <m>sin\,75.67^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Using decimal tables, <m>sin\,75.6^\circ=0.9686</m>.  From the difference column under 
                                <m>7</m> reads <m>0.0003</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Therefore, <md>
                                    <mrow> sin\,75.67^\circ=\amp 0.9686+0.0003</mrow>
                                    <mrow>= \amp 0.9689</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                
                                <m>cos\,75.67^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Using decimal tables, <m>cos\,75.6^\circ=0.2487</m>.  From the difference column under 
                                <m>7</m> reads <m>0.0012</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Therefore, <md>
                                    <mrow> cos\,75.67^\circ=\amp 0.2487-0.0012</mrow>
                                    <mrow>= \amp 0.2475</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                           

                            
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the value of <m>t</m> and <m>w</m> in the figure shown below (Using sine and cosine tables).
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="Triangle14">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        
                        % Draw the triangle
                        \draw [very thick] (0,0) node[left] {$C$} -- (6,0) node[right] {$B$} -- (6,5) node[above] {$A$} -- cycle;
                        
                        % Hypotenuse Label
                        \draw [very thick](3,2.5) node[left] {8 cm};

                        % Right angle symbol at B
                        \draw[very thick] (6,0) -- ++(-0.4,0) -- ++(0,0.4) -- ++(0.4,0);
                        
                        % Sides Labels
                        \node[right] at (6,2.5) {$t$ cm};
                        \node[below] at (3,0) {$w$ cm};

                        % Angle at C
                        \draw [very thick](0.8,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=57.6,radius=0.5];
                        \node[right] at (1,0.4) { $54.7^\circ$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                   
                </image>

            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                   Recall that; 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>sin\,\theta=\frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{Hypotenuse}}=\frac{\text{t}}{8}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>cos\,\theta=\frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{Hypotenuse}}=\frac{\text{w}}{8}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <md>
                        <mrow> sin\,54.7^\circ=\amp \frac{\text{t}}{8}</mrow>
                        <mrow> 8\,sin\,54.7^\circ=\amp \text{t}</mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    But, from tables of sine, <m>sin\,54.7^\circ=0.8161</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <md>
                        <mrow> \text{t} =\amp 8 \times 0.8161 </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 6.5288 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> cos\,54.7^\circ=\amp \frac{\text{w}}{8}</mrow>
                        <mrow> 8\,cos\,54.7^\circ=\amp \text{w}</mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    But, from tables of cosine, <m>cos\,54.7^\circ=0.5779</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <md>
                        <mrow> \text{w} =\amp 8 \times 0.5779 </mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 4.6232 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
 
